17. What is a ClassLoader in Java, what are its types (Bootstrap, Extension, and Application), and how does the class-loading process work 
internally?
Answer : A ClassLoader in Java is a part of the JVM responsible for dynamically loading classes into memory at runtime. It ensures
that classes are loaded only when required and maintains security and namespace separation.
🔹 Types of ClassLoaders
Java uses a hierarchical delegation model with three main class loaders:
Bootstrap ClassLoader
Loads core Java classes (java.lang, java.util)
Part of JVM (written in native code)
Extension (Platform) ClassLoader
Loads classes from jre/lib/ext or platform modules
Handles Java extension libraries
Application (System) ClassLoader
Loads classes from the classpath
Responsible for user-defined classes
 Class Loading Process (Internal Working)
The class loading process follows three main steps:
1. Loading
The ClassLoader reads the .class file
Converts it into a binary representation in memory
2. Linking
This phase has three sub-steps:
Verification → Ensures bytecode is valid and secure
Preparation → Allocates memory for static variables
Resolution → Replaces symbolic references with actual references
3. Initialization
Static variables are assigned values
Static blocks are executed
🔹 Delegation Model (Very Important)
👉 When a class is requested:
Application → Extension → Bootstrap
If not found → child loads it
✔ Prevents duplicate loading
✔ Ensures security

18. How is memory managed in Java, and what are the responsibilities of stack memory, heap
memory, metaspace, and the program counter?
Answer:Memory management in Java is handled automatically by the JVM using runtime memory areas and Garbage Collection (GC).
The JVM divides memory into different regions—Stack, Heap, Metaspace, and Program Counter (PC Register)—each with a specific
responsibility to ensure efficient execution and memory utilization.
1. Stack Memory (Thread-Level, Fast)
Stores method calls, local variables, and references
Each thread has its own stack
Works in LIFO (Last In First Out) manner
Automatically allocated and deallocated
2. Heap Memory (Shared, Object Storage)
Stores objects and instance variables
Shared among all threads
Managed by Garbage Collector
Divided into Young & Old generations
3. Metaspace (Class Metadata Storage)
Stores class definitions, method metadata, static variables
Replaced PermGen (Java 8+)
Grows dynamically (unlike fixed PermGen)
🔹 4. Program Counter (PC Register)
Stores the address of the current executing instruction
Each thread has its own PC register
Helps JVM track execution flow
Stack → manages execution (method calls)
Heap → stores objects
Metaspace → stores class information
PC → tracks instruction execution

19. What is garbage collection, how do heap generations work, what are the commonly used GC algorithms, and why
are -Xms and -Xmx important?
Answer: Garbage Collection (GC) in Java is the process by which the JVM automatically reclaims memory occupied by objects that are no 
longer reachable, ensuring efficient memory usage and preventing memory leaks.
🔹 Heap Generations (How They Work)
Java divides the heap into generations based on object lifecycle:
Young Generation
Where new objects are created
Includes: Eden + Survivor spaces (S0, S1)
Minor GC happens frequently here
Old (Tenured) Generation
Stores long-lived objects
Objects are promoted here after surviving multiple GC cycles
Major (Full) GC occurs here
👉 Idea: Most objects die young → optimize GC performance
🔹 Common GC Algorithms
Serial GC
Single-threaded
Simple but slower (used in small apps)
Parallel GC
Multi-threaded
Focuses on throughput
G1 GC (Garbage First)
Splits heap into regions
Prioritizes regions with most garbage
Low pause time (default in modern Java)
ZGC / Shenandoah
Low-latency collectors
Designed for large-scale applications
🔹 Xms and Xmx (Heap Size Configuration)
-Xms → Initial heap size
-Xmx → Maximum heap size
👉 Why important:
Controls memory allocation
Prevents frequent resizing
Improves performance

20. How does the JVM decide when to perform garbage collection?
The JVM decides to perform Garbage Collection (GC) based on memory pressure and allocation failure, rather than at fixed time
intervals. When the JVM detects that there is insufficient space in the heap (especially in the Young Generation) to allocate
new objects, it triggers a GC cycle to reclaim memory from unreachable objects.

