25. Even if compilation is successful, why might a Java program throw a ClassNotFoundException at runtime?
Even if a Java program compiles successfully, it may throw a ClassNotFoundException at runtime because compilation only checks
for syntax and referenced types at compile-time, not whether the required classes are actually available at runtime in the
classpath.
ClassNotFoundException occurs at runtime when the JVM cannot locate a required class in the classpath, even though the program
compiled successfully, because dynamic class loading depends on runtime availability, not compile-time checks.

